  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use (∞,1)(\\infty,1)-topoi only when your objects are homotopy types and you need sheaf-like gluing at the level of spaces.\n¶Definitions An (∞,1)(\\infty,1)-topos is a presentable (∞,1)(\\infty,1)-category that satisfies higher analogues of the sheaf conditions and descent.\n¶Vocabulary (plain language) Presentable: large enough to have colimits and a set of generators. Descent: the higher-categorical version of gluing. ¶Symbols used X\\mathcal{X}: an (∞,1)(\\infty,1)-topos. ¶Intuition Ordinary topoi are like categories of sheaves of sets. Higher topoi are categories of sheaves of spaces, where equivalences carry homotopy data.\n",
  "name": "(Infinity,1)-Topoi",
